# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1890-louisville-colonels-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1882 Louisville Eclipse season** was the first season as a Major League club for the franchise.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] The team, which had played for several years as a semi-pro team, joined the new American Association league.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1882-louisville-eclipse-season] They finished the season with a 42–38 record, good for third place.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1883 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1883-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 52–45 record, fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1883-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1883 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with a 66–32 record and won the championship of the American Association.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The **1884 Louisville Eclipse season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] The team finished with a 68–40 record, third place in the American Association.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] There has been some debate over whom the manager of this club was, with some sources listing the club's starting second baseman, Joe Gerhardt, as manager for at least part of the year, with others crediting team official Mike Walsh with either all or part of the year.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1884-louisville-eclipse-season] Guy Hecker started 75 games for the Eclipse in 1884 and won the American Association Pitching Triple Crown by leading the league in wins, with 52, strikeouts, with 385, and earned run average with 1.80.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1884 New York Metropolitans** finished with a 75–32 record, first place in the American Association.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] After the season, they played the National League champion Providence Grays in the 1884 World Series and lost three games to zero.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1885-louisville-colonels-season] The **1885 Louisville Colonels season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1885-louisville-colonels-season] The team (formerly the Louisville Eclipse) finished with a 53–59 record, tied for fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] The **1890 Louisville Colonels** baseball team finished with an 88–44 record and won the American Association championship.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] The previous season, the Colonels had lost 111 games, the most any team in the Major Leagues had lost up to that point (the record was broken during the 1890 season by the Pittsburgh Alleghenys, who lost 113 games).
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] When the Colonels won the 1890 pennant, it was the first time in major league history that a team had moved from last place to first place in the span of a single year.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] The Colonels accomplished this largely because of the contributions of two young pitchers, Scott Stratton and Red Ehret.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] Several other players, including outfielder Jimmy Wolf, first baseman Harry Taylor, second baseman Tim Shinnick and shortstop Phil Tomney, provided strong support.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] Veteran manager Jack Chapman was also lauded in the press for providing his young team with steady guidance.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] Yet another factor in the Louisville club's success was that the competition in the American Association was diluted by the advent of the Players' League and by the fact that two of the best AA teams from 1889 moved over to the National League in 1890.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] Although the Louisville club is listed as the "Louisville Colonels" in most sources, the club was actually known as the "Louisville Cyclones" during the 1890 season.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] A deadly tornado (referred to as a cyclone in 1890 parlance) swept through Louisville in March 1890, killing 115-120 people.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] When the local baseball team began showing signs of dominance early in the 1890 baseball season, the club was dubbed "the Cyclones." It continued to be referred to by that name the rest of the season, then switched back to "Colonels" the following year.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] After the season, Louisville played the NL champions, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms, in the 1890 World Series.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] The Bridegrooms were one of the teams that had jumped to the NL, and had been the champions of the AA in 1889.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] The World Series wound up in a 3–3–1 tie.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] Louisville, champions of the American Association, played the National League champions, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms in the 1890 World Series.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] The series pitted the two most recent American Association champions against each other.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] The series winner was to be the first to win four games.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] Brooklyn started strong, winning the first two games in Louisville, with game 3 called after eight innings with the score tied.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] Louisville salvaged the fourth game, which was the last one played in Louisville.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] After Brooklyn won the first game at home to take a 3–1 lead, Louisville came back to win two straight.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] After that, bad weather and poor attendance forced the remaining games to be canceled, with the plan that a deciding game would be played before the 1891 season began.
[src:1890-louisville-colonels-season/1890-louisville-colonels-season] However, due to inter-league disputes, that never occurred, and the series officially ended in a 3–3–1 tie.
